\section{Helmholtz Lagrangian}

In this section we will introduce the so called {\it Helmholtz Lagrangian}. It is defined as follows:

text:
\begin{equation}
L_H = \sqrt g [
{\varphi} {\mathcal R} - {\varphi} r({\varphi}) + f(r({\varphi})) 
]+ {\mathcal L}_{Mat}(g,\psi)
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
{\varphi} \tilde R_{{\beta}\nu} = T_{\mu\nu} + \frac{1}{2} f(r({\varphi}))g_{{\beta}\nu} \\
\tilde\nabla_{\lambda} (\sqrt g {\varphi} g^{\mu\nu}) = 0 \\
{\mathcal R} = r({\varphi})\\
E_i = 0
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\begin{equation}
L_E(\tilde g_{\mu\nu}, \tilde{\Gamma}^{\lambda}_{\mu\nu}, {\varphi}, \psi^i) =
\sqrt{\tilde g} (\tilde g^{\mu\nu} \tilde R_{\mu\nu} + {\varphi}^{-2}(f(r({\varphi})) - {\varphi} r({\varphi}))) + {\mathcal L}_{Mat}({\varphi}^{-1}\tilde g, \psi)
\end{equation}
